### Spring Bean Scopes

Spring supports several bean scopes that control the lifecycle and visibility of beans.

### Scope Types

| Scope | Description |
|---|---|
| **Singleton** (default) | One instance per Spring IoC container. Shared across the entire application. |
| **Prototype** | A new instance is created every time the bean is requested. |
| **Request** | One instance per HTTP request. Available only in web-aware contexts. |
| **Session** | One instance per HTTP session. Available only in web-aware contexts. |
| **Application** | One instance per ServletContext. Similar to singleton but scoped to the ServletContext. |

### @Scope Annotation

```java
@Component
@Scope("prototype")
public class ShoppingCart {
    // A new cart for each injection point
}

@Component
@Scope(value = WebApplicationContext.SCOPE_SESSION, proxyMode = ScopedProxyMode.TARGET_CLASS)
public class UserPreferences {
    // Separate preferences per user session
}
```

### Proxy Mode for Web Scopes

Request and session scoped beans require a proxy because the singleton beans that inject them exist longer. Spring creates a proxy that delegates to the actual request/session-scoped instance.

### Singleton vs Prototype

- **Singleton**: Stateless services, utility classes, DAOs/repositories
- **Prototype**: Stateful beans, shopping carts, per-operation helpers

codeExample:
@Component
@Scope(value = "prototype")
public class PaymentProcessor {
    private final PaymentGateway gateway;

    public PaymentProcessor(PaymentGateway gateway) {
        this.gateway = gateway;
        System.out.println("New PaymentProcessor instance created");
    }

    public PaymentResult process(Order order) {
        return gateway.charge(order.getTotal());
    }
}
